comments.body:
Hi, author of https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/issues/135377 here. This doesn't appear to resolve the problem. I built your branch and I'm still see calls to `<std::__n4861::coroutine_handlestd::__n4861::noop_coroutine_promise::__frame::__dummy_resume_destroy()>` happening in my code, even in simple cases. I noticed that your comment says "If a coro.noop ends up having no users" , but I would hope that it could be elided in a case where there is a possible user.

The most common use case for this is a simple `await_suspend` like this:
```cpp
std::coroutine_handle<> await_suspend(std::coroutine_handle<> Handle) {
    if (this_executor == target_executor) {
      // resume inline via symmetric transfer
      return Handle;
    } else {
      target_executor->post(Handle);
      return std::noop_coroutine();
    }
}
```

In this case, we get some generated assembly that looks like (pseudocode)
```cpp

if (this_executor == target_executor) {
  %rdi = Handle
} else {
  %rdi = std::__n4861::coroutine_handle<std::__n4861::noop_coroutine_promise>::_S_fr
}
jmpq *(%rdi)
```

What I'd like for this to generate instead is:
```cpp
if (this_executor == target_executor) {
  %rdi = Handle
  jmpq *(%rdi)
} else {
  ret
}
```

That is, the optimizer understands that std::__n4861::coroutine_handle<std::__n4861::noop_coroutine_promise>::_S_fr is a special thing that does nothing, and removes it completely:
- don't load the frame address - currently there are multiple redundant instructions like
`0x55555556ccef: leaq   0x16572(%rip), %r15       ; std::__n4861::coroutine_handle<std::__n4861::noop_coroutine_promise>::_S_fr`
- if it can determine that this would be called, just replace it with a simple `ret` instruction instead.

Obviously this is only possible as a local optimization - if this value might be stored and passed to a different function or data structure, then we would need to preserve existing behavior
